<p>&nbsp;The program combines structured classroom instruction with cultural exposure. Students can take part in daily social and cultural activities, as well as weekend excursions and field trips. Teaching is student-centered, encouraging active participation so learners are more engaged in the process of acquiring a second language and can progress more quickly.</p>
<p>&nbsp;At the beginning of the course, each student undergoes an assessment. Based on this, the teacher prepares a detailed weekly lesson plan using the GANAG framework. This plan outlines daily learning objectives, evaluations, homework, and structured methods such as thinking maps and logical sequencing to ensure consistent progress throughout the week.</p>
<p>&nbsp;The teaching approach is based on Stephen Krashen’s theory of comprehensible input. Lessons begin with the introduction of a topic, followed by students reading and forming their own understanding of rules. Teachers then provide feedback through discussion, and students reinforce their learning by listening or watching explanations. Practice takes place through oral and written exercises, followed by further feedback, quick quizzes, and evaluations. Homework and additional tests are used to identify weak areas and reinforce understanding.</p>
<p>&nbsp;The cost of the accelerated program is the same as other programs offered by the school, with tuition set at 200 US dollars per week and an additional 100 US dollars per week for homestay accommodation. Students interested in earning college credit can explore the academic program for further details.</p>
<p>&nbsp;For those seeking different learning styles, the school also offers alternative programs. These include a more flexible Spanish for Travelers course, a regular immersion program at a standard pace, advanced studies focused on the Spanish subjunctive, and a current events curriculum that explores social and political topics in Guatemala for intermediate and advanced learners.</p>
<p>&nbsp;Casa Xelajú has built a strong reputation with over 38 years of experience and more than 12,000 students from around the world. The school follows official academic standards and uses recognized textbooks such as Spanish Now Level 1 and Level 2. Students are also encouraged to use supplementary materials like a bilingual dictionary and verb reference books.</p>
<p>&nbsp;The immersion experience includes a comprehensive set of services. Students receive five hours of one-on-one Spanish instruction each day, five days a week, in private study spaces designed to minimize distractions. Cultural activities are offered daily, and accommodation with a Guatemalan family includes a private room and three meals per day, except on Sundays when meals are not provided. Additional benefits include free high-speed internet, access to lectures and conferences, complimentary coffee, tea, and bread during breaks, and use of the school’s library. Optional services such as laundry and weaving lessons are available for an extra fee.</p>
<p>&nbsp;The program is accredited by the Guatemalan Ministry of Education. After submitting an application, students receive detailed information about travel, climate, clothing, and recommended reading to help them prepare for their stay.</p>
<p>&nbsp;Classes are not held on certain holidays, although students are still required to pay for that week due to labor regulations. Despite this, the school maintains high satisfaction rates and emphasizes a well-rounded immersion experience that combines language learning with cultural understanding.</p>
